 next generation radio telescope that will operate in the\nfrequency range of 0.05 - 20 GHz with unprecedented sensitivities and\nresolutions. The expected detection limits of SKA will reveal a few hundred to\nthousand new radio halos, relics and mini-halos providing the first large and\ncomprehensive samples for their study. The wide frequency coverage along with\nsensitivity to extended structures will be able to constrain the CR\nacceleration mechanisms. The higher frequency (> 5 GHz) observations will be\nable to use the Sunyaev-Zel'dovich effect to probe the ICM pressure in addition\nto the tracers such as lobes of head-tail radio sources. The SKA also opens\nprospects to detect the \"off-state\" radio emission from the ICM predicted by\nthe hadronic models and the turbulent re-acceleration models. [abridged]\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 26 Oct 2016 05:48:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-11-23"}
